<br />Well, there are all those new Famiclones and NES-clones being produced, and even Nintendo claims they're somewhat sorta bringing back the NES with the Wii.  I'd consider all that to be modern, though not in the same sense you mean.  No doubt though that games would need to have insanely good production quality to get much attention outside of the usual NESdev/homebrew community.  Meeting modern expectations on antique platform is a pretty interesting challenge, I know from designing (but far from fully programming) a game I was working on. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>

