					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">There are problems with making and selling games for famiclones:
<br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>It's hard to find famiclones in many parts of the United States. </li><li>It's harder to find famiclones that aren't bundled with flagrantly pirated software. Famiclones are legal as of 2005 when Nintendo's and Ricoh's 20-year patents run out, but copyrights on Nintendo software will outlive you. </li><li>It's harder to find famiclones without major compatibility problems, such as timing errors (hurts Rare games), incorrect fetch sequences (hurts MMC5), incorrect APU pulse duty cycle, and the like. </li><li>It's harder to find famiclones with a responsive controller. </li></ol>There are also problems with making and selling games for modern consoles: <ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Console makers use a digital signature to restrict what programs their consoles can run, and a license isn't available to small companies. </li></ol>There are also problems with making and selling games for PCs: <ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>The market is saturated. </li><li>Virtually no PC game players have multiple joypads and a TV-out, which are necessary for "party" style multiplayer games. </li></ol>There are also problems with making and selling games for smart phones: <ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>The market is saturated. </li><li>Mobile phone D-pads tend to be unresponsive. </li><li>Many network operators use a digital signature to restrict what programs their phones can run, and a license isn't available to small companies. </li></ol></div>

