						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Hey, why did you make me the first post of this splitted thred ? It makes me look like avid of money.</div><br />Sorry, wasn't me, but splitting a topic doesn't normally allow for clean cuts.  I added a note to the first post though.  I'm sure noone is here to make money, otherwise they'd be off somewhere else doing something boring and/or exploitive, heheh.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't think Joe Gamer cares about that. And although there are a few games that have trouble running on famiclones, I doubt that modern developers will make abuse of timing tricks, as it's hardly necessary in a real game.<br /></div><br />As long as the CPU and PPU background are timed properly, and $2005 and $2006 work properly (and they surely do, otherwise almost every racing game and such would be broken), that's about the extent of useful timing tricks for games.<br /><br />But there is that stupid sound problem, with 2 of the pulse duty cycle settings being reversed, on the Power Joy II that I have.  That's about the extent of the annoyance I've seen, though I know other clones don't have that problem.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">In the United States, where can I order an accurate famiclone that doesn't come packed with a pirate multicart?</div><br />If you hate the pirate cart that much, just don't play it. Burn it if it makes you happy. You are taking this piracy thing to an extreme, man. Relax. And I'm sure there are quality famiclones that don't come with any carts (my pokefami, for example, didn't have one).<br /></div>
<br />
<br />Here in the US, the really common Famiclones actually have pirated games internally, that's probably what he's referring to.  Like on my Power Joy II, if there's no cart in the slot then it comes up with a menu that has hacked versions of Duck Hunt, Hogan's Alley, Tengen Tetris, stuff like that.  They were being sold everywhere, advertised on TV, in booths in malls, until (presumably Nintendo) or someone started cracking down on it.
<br />
<br />I'm sure the more legit clone systems can be mail-ordered, I'm not sure where the best distributor is though.</div>

